<section class="style-guide__section">
  <div class="type--base">
    <dl class="type--dl">
      <dt class="type--dt">Description List</dt>
      <dd class="type--dd">A list of terms and their description</dd>
      <dt class="type--dt">Another term</dt>
      <dd class="type--dd">And its definition</dd>
    </dl>
  </div>
  <div class="type">
    <p>
      Description lists are used to display terms and their related description and are made up of two parts: terms and description. Description lists are often used for lists of terms and their definitions. Description lists <em>must</em> use the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/dl"><code>dl</code></a> element and can be styled through the <code>.type--dl</code> class.
    </p>
    <p>
      Terms <em>must</em> use the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/dt"><code>dt</code></a> element and can be styled through the <code>.type--dt</code> class.
    </p>
    <p>
      Descriptions <em>must</em> use the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/dd"><code>dd</code></a> element and can be styled through the <code>.type--dd</code> class.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="style-guide__section">
  <div class="type--base">
    <ul class="type--list">
      <li class="type--list-item">Unordered List</li>
      <li class="type--list-item">With styling</li>
    </ul>
    <ol class="type--list">
      <li class="type--list-item">Ordered List</li>
      <li class="type--list-item">With styling</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
  <div class="type">
    <p>
      Both ordered and unordered lists share the same styling, making it easy to style. The list wrapper <em>must</em> use <em>either</em> the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/ul"><code>ul</code></a> element (for unordered lists) or the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/ol"><code>ol</code></a> element (for ordered lists) and can be styled through the <code>.type--list</code> class. List items <em>must</em> use the the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/li"><code>li</code></a> element and can be styled through the <code>.type--list-item</code> class.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="style-guide__section">
  <p class="type--base"><kbd class="type--kbd">K</kbd>+<kbd class="type--kbd">B</kbd>+<kbd class="type--kbd">D</kbd></p>
  <div class="type">
    <p>
      KBD is meant to represent keyboard input. Each key in a keyboard sequence <em>must</em> use the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/kbd"><code>kbd</code></a> element and can be styled through the <code>.type--kbd</code> element.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="style-guide__section">
  <div class="style-guide__separate-items">
    <blockquote class="type--quote">
      <p>These quotes are super cool! They've got internationalized quotes surrounding the main copy, which I think is super tool. You can even have one more more paragraphs and the quotes only wrap around the first and last items!</p>
      <p>They support citations too! Add them normally with a <code class="type--code">footer</code> element, or, if you're working in Markdown, follow your blockquote section with a paragraph and the <code class="type--code">{.cite}</code> attribute to have it automagically converted into a blockquote footer.</p>
      <footer>
        <p>Style Guide Author</p>
      </footer>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote class="type--quote" lang="fr">
      <p>Ceci est une citation qui est écrite en français! Remarquez les différentes citations basées sur <code class="type--code">lang="fr"</code>.</p>
    </blockquote>
  </div>
  <div class="type">
    <p>Quotes are meant to emphasize extended quotations, be it from the current source or an external source, optionally with some form of citation. They <em>must</em> use the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/blockquote">blockquote</a> element and can be styled through the <code>.type--quote</code> class.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="style-guide__section">
  <div class="style-guide__separate-items">
    <aside class="message">
      <p><strong>Info:</strong> This is a <code>message</code>, used to convey non-critical information to a user.</p>
    </aside>
    <aside class="message--note message">
      <p><strong>Note:</strong> This is a <code>message--note</code>, used to convey important, but not critical, information to a user.</p>
    </aside>
    <aside class="message--warning message">
      <p><strong>Warning:</strong> This is a <code>message--warning</code>, used to convey critical information to a user.</p>
    </aside>
    <aside class="message--tip message">
      <p><strong>Tip:</strong> This is a <code>message--tip</code>, used to convey helpful but not required information to a user.</p>
    </aside>
  </div>
  <div class="type">
    <p>Messages are used as call-outs to direct readers users to additional, often important, information. They come in four flavors, <code>info</code>, <code>note</code>, <code>warning</code>, and <code>tip</code>, with <code>info</code> being the default. The <code>note</code> version should be used when there's something the user should pay attention to but is not critical. The <code>warning</code> version should be used when there's something critical the user <em>must</em> know. The <code>tip</code> version should be used when there's additional helpful information for the user. If none of the above options make sense, the standard <code>info</code> version should be used.</p>
    <p>Messages usually use the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/aside">aside</a> element and can be styled by using the <code>.message</code> class as well as optionally one of the modifiers <code>.message--note</code>, <code>.message--warning</code>, <code>.message--tip</code></p>
  </div>
</section>
